<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-06-26T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-06-26T00:00:00-05:00" n="490" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d490">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">585.61B1/574½</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Conversation, by the Acting
                                    Secretary of State</hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-06-26">June 26,
                                    1941</date>.</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>Lord Halifax<note n="28" xml:id="d490fn28">British Ambassador.</note>
                                called to see me this morning.</p>
                            <p>The Ambassador left with me an <hi rend="italic">aide-mémoire</hi><note n="29" xml:id="d490fn29">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Infra</hi>.</note> expressing the view of the
                                British Government that the International Load-Line Convention
                                should be modified so as to permit cargo-carrying ships, including
                                tankers, to load more deeply than is now permitted under the terms
                                of the Convention. I told the Ambassador that that likewise
                                represented the views of this Government.</p>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>